e is also found in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Barwick","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Berwick or Barwick, for example in Northumberland, Norfolk, Somerset, and Yorkshire, from Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying farm building’, i.e. a granary lying some distance away from the main settlement.","North German: habitational name from a place called Berwick, near Soest, in Westphalia."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Emma Barton was born in 1180. She had at least 1 son with Sir William Barton. She died in 1267, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 87."},"et":{"1180–1267":"1180–1267","1180–1236":"1180–1236","1200–1300":"1200–1300","1236":"1236","1267":"1267","1300":"1300","1200":"1200","1180":"1180","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Yorkshire England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1180–1267":"1180–1267","1180–1236":"1180–1236","1200–1300":"1200–1300","1236":"1236","1267":"1267","1300":"1300","1200":"1200","1180":"1180","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Yorkshire England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1180–1267":"1180–1267","1180–1236":"1180–1236","1200–1300":"1200–1300","1236":"1236","1267":"1267","1300":"1300